   579→## Docs
   581→Dotenv exposes four functions:
   582→
   583→* `config`
   584→* `parse`
   585→* `populate`
   586→
   587→### Config
   589→`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590→[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591→and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592→
   593→```js
   594→const result = dotenv.config()
   595→
   596→if (result.error) {
   597→  throw result.error
   598→}
   599→
   600→console.log(result.parsed)
   601→```
   602→
   603→You can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604→
   605→#### Options …
   607→##### path
   609→Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610→
   611→Specify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612→
   613→```js
   614→require('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615→```
   616→
   617→By default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618→
   619→Pass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620→
   621→```js  
   622→require('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623→```
   624→
   625→##### quiet
   627→Default: `false`
   628→
   629→Suppress runtime logging message.
   630→
   631→```js
   632→// index.js
   633→require('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634→console.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635→```
   636→
   637→```ini
   638→# .env
   639→HELLO=World
   640→```
   641→
   642→```sh
   643→$ node index.js
   644→[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645→Hello World
   646→```
   647→
   648→##### encoding
   650→Default: `utf8`
   651→
   652→Specify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653→
   654→```js
   655→require('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656→```
   657→
   658→##### debug
   660→Default: `false`
   661→
   662→Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663→
   664→```js
   665→require('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666→```
   667→
   668→##### override
   670→Default: `false`
   671→
   672→Override any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673→
   674→```js
   675→require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676→```
   677→
   678→##### processEnv
   680→Default: `process.env`
   681→
   682→Specify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683→
   684→```js
   685→const myObject = {}
   686→require('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687→
   688→console.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689→console.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690→```
   691→
   692→### Parse
   694→The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695→variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696→an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697→
   698→```js
   699→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700→const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701→const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702→console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703→```
   704→
   705→#### Options …
   707→##### debug
   709→Default: `false`
   710→
   711→Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712→
   713→```js
   714→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715→const buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716→const opt = { debug: true }
   717→const config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718→// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719→```
   720→
   721→### Populate
   723→The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724→
   725→For example, customizing the source:
   726→
   727→```js
   728→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729→const parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730→
   731→dotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732→
   733→console.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734→```
   735→
   736→For example, customizing the source AND target:
   737→
   738→```js
   739→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740→const parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741→const target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742→
   743→dotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744→
   745→console.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746→```
   747→
   748→#### options …
   750→##### Debug
   752→Default: `false`
   753→
   754→Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755→
   756→##### override
   758→Default: `false`
   759→
   760→Override any environment variables that have already been set.
   761→
   762→&nbsp;
   763→
   764→## CHANGELOG
   766→See [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767→
   768→&nbsp;
